["OBL-CD-003","FCA PS22/9 — Consumer Duty","PS22/9 Chapter 5 — Price and Value Outcome","Ensure the price consumers pay for a product is reasonable given the benefits received; complete a Fair Value Assessment for each retail product; remediate where products found to deliver poor value","Conduct","FCA","31 Jul 2023","No direct US equivalent. US fair lending law addresses discriminatory pricing but there is no equivalent affirmative duty to assess and demonstrate fair value across all retail products.","Covered","CTL-COM-003","FVA for each retail product; Product Governance Committee approval; remediation plan where poor value identified; SMF16 annual Consumer Duty board report","SMF16",""],
["OBL-CD-004","FCA PS22/9 — Consumer Duty","PS22/9 Chapter 6 — Consumer Understanding Outcome","Ensure all communications (including financial promotions, key features documents and terms) are clear, fair and not misleading; test comprehension with target market consumers; monitor post-release","Conduct","FCA","31 Jul 2023","No direct US equivalent requiring comprehension testing of communications with target market consumers before release","Covered","CTL-COM-004","Comprehension testing report with methodology, sample size and score; pass/fail record; post-release complaint analysis","SMF16",""],
["OBL-CD-005","FCA PS22/9 — Consumer Duty","PS22/9 Chapter 7 — Consumer Support Outcome","Ensure consumers receive adequate support that is at least as accessible as the sales or application process; adapt support for customers with vulnerability characteristics","Conduct","FCA","31 Jul 2023","No direct US equivalent. FCA FG21/1 Guidance on Vulnerability characterises this as requiring proactive identification and adapted handling — more prescriptive than US vulnerable customer guidance","Covered","CTL-COM-005","Vulnerable customer flag rate; adapted handling records; specialist team referral log; channel availability evidence showing support equals sales accessibility","SMF16","No direct US equivalent — vulnerability identification and adapted handling under FCA FG21/1 is UK-specific"],
["OBL-DISP-001","FCA Handbook — DISP","DISP 1.3.1R — What Constitutes a Complaint","A complaint is any expression of dissatisfaction whether oral or written, and whether justified or not, from a person about the firm's provision of, or failure to provide, a financial service; must be handled under formal DISP process","Conduct","FCA","1 Nov 2007","UK DISP definition of complaint is broader than US CFPB definition; includes informal verbal expressions of dissatisfaction; under-recording is a recurring FCA supervisory finding","Covered","CTL-COM-001","Complaint intake log showing channel, product, receipt date, and initial category; QA miscategorisation report","SMF16",""],
["OBL-DISP-002","FCA Handbook — DISP","DISP 1.6.2R — 8-Week Resolution Deadline","Send the complainant a final response no later than 8 weeks after receiving the complaint; where unable to respond within 8 weeks, send a holding letter explaining the delay and advising of FOS referral rights","Conduct","FCA","1 Nov 2007","UK 8-week hard deadline with automatic FOS jurisdiction trigger. US CFPB complaint framework does not have an equivalent universal binding deadline.","Covered","CTL-COM-002","SLA tracker report by age cohort; breach register with same-day SMF16 notification record; final response date in complaint management system","SMF16","UK-specific hard deadline with automatic FOS referral trigger — no direct US equivalent"],
["OBL-DISP-003","FCA Handbook — DISP","DISP 1.10.2R — Complaints Data Return to FCA","Submit a report to the FCA twice yearly showing the number of complaints received, the products and services they relate to, and the outcome and time taken to resolve them","Conduct","FCA","1 Jan 2006","No direct US equivalent mandatory biannual complaints data submission to the regulator of this scope and format","Covered","CTL-COM-001; CTL-COM-002","Biannual FCA complaints data return with submission confirmation; internal MI reconciliation to return data","SMF16","FCA publishes complaints data — public reputational signal"],
["OBL-DISP-004","FCA Handbook — DISP","DISP 1.2.1R — Independent and Impartial Investigation","Investigate complaints competently, diligently and impartially; not be biased in favour of the firm","Conduct","FCA","1 Nov 2007","No direct equivalent — UK FCA requires evidence of genuine impartiality, not just procedural compliance; FOS uphold rates are used as a proxy measure for investigative quality","Covered","CTL-COM-001; CTL-COM-002","QA review records of complaint investigation quality; FOS uphold rate tracking; investigation workpaper evidence","SMF16",""],
["OBL-DISP-005","FCA Handbook — DISP","DISP 1.5.4R — Vulnerable Customer Handling in Complaints","Take into account the individual circumstances of each complainant, including any characteristics of vulnerability, and adapt the complaints handling process accordingly","Conduct","FCA","1 Nov 2007","UK explicit requirement to adapt complaints handling for vulnerability; linked to FCA FG21/1 and Consumer Duty Outcome 4","Covered","CTL-COM-005","CRM vulnerability flag in complaints records; adapted handling record for vulnerable complainants; specialist team referral log","SMF16",""],
["OBL-SMCR-001","FSMA 2000; FCA SUP 10C","FSMA 2000 s.59; SUP 10C.2.1R — SMF Pre-Approval","An individual may not perform a Senior Management Function at a firm unless approved in advance by the FCA and/or PRA; it is a criminal offence to perform a controlled function without approval","Accountability","FCA / PRA","7 Mar 2016","UK requires advance regulator approval for SMF appointments. US does not require advance regulator pre-approval for senior management appointments — US uses post-appointment notification or supervisory review.","Covered","CTL-SMC-001","FCA/PRA approval letter for each current SMF holder; SMF register; Form A submission records","SMF1 (CEO); all SMF holders","No direct US equivalent — criminal offence provision for unapproved appointments is UK-specific"],
["OBL-SMCR-002","FSMA 2000; FCA SUP 10C","FSMA 2000 s.60; FCA SUP 10C.11R — Statement of Responsibilities","Each SMF holder must have a Statement of Responsibilities approved by the firm setting out the aspects of the firm's affairs they are responsible for; must be submitted to FCA/PRA on appointment and on material change","Accountability","FCA / PRA","7 Mar 2016","Statement of Responsibilities is a personal document with no direct US equivalent — US Senior Managers do not produce individual responsibility statements filed with their regulator","Covered","CTL-SMC-002","Current SoR document for each SMF holder with version number and date; FCA/PRA submission confirmation","All SMF holders","No direct US equivalent — personal regulatory document filed with regulator"],
["OBL-SMCR-003","FSMA 2000; FCA SUP 10C","FCA SUP 10C.12R — Management Responsibilities Map","Each dual-regulated firm must maintain a Management Responsibilities Map showing all SMF holders, their prescribed responsibilities, and reporting lines; must be submitted to FCA/PRA and updated on material change","Accountability","FCA / PRA","7 Mar 2016","Management Responsibilities Map is a firm-level accountability document with no direct US equivalent","Covered","CTL-SMC-005","MRM document with version number and date; change log; FCA/PRA submission confirmation for each version","SMF1 (CEO)","No direct US equivalent"],
["OBL-SMCR-004","FSMA 2000; FSMA 2000 s.66A","FSMA 2000 s.66A — SMF Misconduct (Reasonable Steps Standard)","An SMF holder is guilty of misconduct if a breach occurs in the area for which they are responsible and they did not take such steps as a person in their position could reasonably be expected to take to avoid the breach occurring; applies regardless of direct involvement","Accountability","FCA / PRA","7 Mar 2016","The Reasonable Steps standard creates personal statutory liability for SMF holders — structurally different from US Heightened Standards which impose institutional obligations without equivalent personal statutory liability","Covered","CTL-SMC-006","SMF quarterly assurance pack; decision log; escalation records; board committee attendance and contribution evidence","All SMF holders","Central SMCR personal accountability obligation — no direct US equivalent with equivalent statutory force"],
["OBL-SMCR-005","FCA Handbook — COCON","COCON 2.1.1R — Individual Conduct Rules (IC1-IC6)","All relevant individuals (SMF holders, Certified Persons, and other conduct rules staff) must: act with integrity; act with due care, skill and diligence; be open and cooperative with regulators; not engage in market abuse; observe proper standards of market conduct; and (IC6 since 2023) act to deliver good outcomes for retail customers under Consumer Duty","Accountability","FCA","7 Mar 2016 (IC6 added 31 Jul 2023)","UK Conduct Rules apply broadly across bank staff with breach reporting via Form REP008. US has no equivalent set of personal conduct rules with a reporting obligation to the regulator.","Covered","CTL-SMC-004","Conduct Rules training completion records; breach investigation records; Form REP008 submissions where applicable","All SMF holders; all Certified Persons; all staff subject to Conduct Rules","No direct US equivalent personal conduct rules with regulator reporting obligation"],
["OBL-SMCR-006","FCA Handbook — SYSC 10A","SYSC 10A.2R — Certification Regime","Firms must not permit a person to perform a Significant Harm Function unless the firm is satisfied the person is fit and proper; fitness and propriety must be assessed at least annually; a written certificate must be issued confirming fitness and propriety","Accountability","FCA","7 Mar 2016","UK requires annual F&P certification with written certificate for all Significant Harm Functions — no equivalent US requirement for annual written F&P certification of material risk takers at this scope","Covered","CTL-SMC-003","F&P assessment record; F&P certificate with issue date; annual overdue report showing 0 outstanding","SMF16 (for framework design)","No direct US equivalent annual written certification requirement"],
["OBL-SMCR-007","FSMA 2000; COCON","COCON 4.1 — Senior Manager Conduct Rules SC1-SC4","Senior Managers must: take reasonable steps to ensure the business for which they are responsible is controlled effectively (SC1); take reasonable steps to ensure business complies with relevant regulatory requirements and standards (SC2); take reasonable steps to ensure any delegation is to an appropriate person and monitored (SC3); disclose appropriately any information the FCA/PRA would reasonably expect (SC4)","Accountability","FCA / PRA","7 Mar 2016","SC4 disclosure obligation is particularly distinctive — senior managers must proactively disclose information to regulators that goes beyond what is specifically requested; no equivalent US personal obligation to proactively disclose to regulator","Covered","CTL-SMC-006","SMF assurance pack; escalation and disclosure records; regulatory correspondence log for each SMF","All SMF holders","SC4 proactive disclosure obligation is UK-specific with no exact US equivalent"],
["OBL-SMCR-008","FCA Handbook — SYSC 22","SYSC 22.2.1R — Regulatory References","When providing a regulatory reference for a former employee who held an SMF, Certified Person, or other in-scope role, firms must disclose all information that the firm reasonably considers to be relevant to the receiving firm's assessment of fitness and propriety","Accountability","FCA","7 Mar 2016","UK regulatory references regime requires mandatory disclosure of disciplinary findings — stricter than US employment reference practices which may be limited to dates of employment for legal risk reasons","Covered","CTL-SMC-001 (links to F&P process)","Regulatory reference request and response records; regulatory reference drafts and approval; disclosure of all relevant disciplinary matters","SMF16",""],
["OBL-OPRES-001","PRA/FCA PS21/3; SS1/21","PS21/3 para 2.1-2.9 — IBS Identification","Identify the firm's Important Business Services — the services whose disruption would cause intolerable harm to consumers, threaten UK financial stability, or compromise market integrity; document an IBS register","Operational Resilience","PRA / FCA","31 Mar 2022 (identification); 31 Mar 2025 (full compliance)","UK PS21/3 IBS regime is more prescriptive than US FFIEC BCM handbook guidance — impact tolerance requirements and board-approved self-assessment submission are UK-specific","Covered","CTL-OPR-001","IBS register with IBS names, ownership and review dates; board approval record; most recent PRA/FCA submission","SMF4","No direct US equivalent for the board-approved, regulator-submitted IBS self-assessment requirement"],
["OBL-OPRES-002","PRA/FCA PS21/3; SS1/21","PS21/3 para 2.10-2.16 — Impact Tolerances","Set, document and test against impact tolerances for each IBS — the maximum tolerable level of disruption measured in appropriate metrics (e.g. time, volume of transactions affected, financial loss)","Operational Resilience","PRA / FCA","31 Mar 2022","No direct US equivalent for quantified, board-approved impact tolerances per IBS","Covered","CTL-OPR-002","Impact tolerance documentation for each IBS with board approval; scenario test results showing whether tolerances met; gap remediation plans where tolerances breached","SMF4","No direct US equivalent"],
["OBL-OPRES-003","PRA/FCA PS21/3; SS1/21","PS21/3 para 2.17-2.23 — Severe-But-Plausible Scenarios","Test the ability to remain within impact tolerances in a range of severe but plausible scenarios; scenarios must include operational disruption from technology failures, third-party provider failures, cyber incidents and people-related incidents","Operational Resilience","PRA / FCA","31 Mar 2022","The UK severe-but-plausible scenario testing requirement combined with impact tolerance measurement is more structured than US resilience testing requirements","Covered","CTL-OPR-002","Scenario test design documentation; test execution record and results; tolerance breach analysis; post-test remediation plan","SMF4",""],
["OBL-OPRES-004","PRA/FCA PS21/3; PRA SS2/21","SS2/21 para 6.1-6.7 — Material Outsourcing Pre-Notification","Notify the PRA before entering into any material outsourcing arrangement; provide the PRA with sufficient notice to enable it to assess the impact of the arrangement on the firm's operational resilience","Operational Resilience","PRA","6 Jul 2022","UK requires advance notification to PRA before commencing material outsourcing — US has no equivalent pre-notification requirement for outsourcing arrangements","Covered","CTL-OPR-003","PRA pre-notification submission confirmation; material outsourcing register entry with notification date","SMF4","No direct US equivalent for pre-notification requirement — UK-specific"],
["OBL-OPRES-005","FSMA 2023 Part 6A — Critical Third Parties","FSMA 2023 Part 6A; PRA/FCA CTP Rules (effective March 2025)","Firms must comply with requirements relating to designated Critical Third Parties; apply enhanced oversight; participate in regulator-led CTP exercises; manage concentration risk; notify regulators of material changes in CTP relationships","Operational Resilience","PRA / FCA","March 2025","UK FSMA 2023 Part 6A CTP regime is a UK-specific innovation giving regulators direct powers over third-party service providers — no equivalent regime in EU (DORA) or US at time of writing","Covered","CTL-OPR-004","Annual CTP oversight assessment; concentration risk analysis; AWS incident notification triage log; PRA information gathering responses","SMF4","No direct EU or US equivalent for direct regulator oversight of third-party providers — UK-specific FSMA 2023 innovation"],
["OBL-OPRES-006","PRA/FCA PS21/3","PS21/3 para 2.24-2.30 — Annual Self-Assessment","Produce, review and document an annual assessment of the firm's operational resilience; the assessment must be approved by the board and be available to the PRA and FCA on request; must include lessons learned from incidents and scenario tests","Operational Resilience","PRA / FCA","31 Mar 2022","UK board-approved, regulator-available annual self-assessment is more formal and personalised than US BCM documentation requirements","Covered","CTL-OPR-001; CTL-OPR-002","Annual self-assessment document; board approval record; PRA/FCA submission confirmation","SMF4",""],
["OBL-OPRES-007","PRA/FCA PS21/3; SS1/21","PS21/3 para 2.31-2.35 — Dependency Mapping","Map the resources — people, processes, technology, facilities and information — necessary to deliver each IBS; identify dependencies on third parties including material outsourcers and CTPs","Operational Resilience","PRA / FCA","31 Mar 2022","UK dependency mapping at IBS level with explicit third-party dependency identification is more granular than US BCM asset identification requirements","Covered","CTL-OPR-001","IBS dependency maps for each IBS with version history; third-party dependency identification for each IBS; change management integration log showing dependency map updates","SMF4",""],
["OBL-MIFIR-001","UK-MiFIR (SI 2017/701 as retained and amended)","UK SI 2017/701 Art.26 — Transaction Reporting Obligation","Report details of all transactions in financial instruments traded on UK trading venues to the FCA within T+1; report must include prescribed fields (currently ~65 fields) including LEI, instrument identifiers, timestamps, price and quantity","Market Integrity","FCA","3 Jan 2018 (UK application)","UK-MiFIR has diverged from EU-MiFIR post-Brexit in specific field specifications, FIRDS reference data requirements and FCA-specific reporting guidance. Firms with EU operations maintain parallel UK and EU reporting stacks.","Covered","CTL-CAP-001","Pre-submission validation log; ARM submission confirmation with FCA acknowledgement; daily reconciliation sign-off","SMF16","Post-Brexit divergence from EU-MiFIR — parallel reporting stacks required for EU-operating firms"],
["OBL-MIFIR-002","UK-MiFIR; FCA MAR 10","FCA MAR 10.2.1R — Transaction Reporting Systems and Controls","Establish effective systems and controls to ensure complete and accurate transaction reporting to the FCA; maintain a documented testing programme; address reporting errors promptly","Market Integrity","FCA","3 Jan 2018","No direct equivalent — US trade reporting is to DTCC/FINRA under different regulatory structures without equivalent FCA-specific systems and controls obligation","Covered","CTL-CAP-001","Systems and controls documentation for transaction reporting; testing programme results; error correction log with timeliness","SMF16",""],
["OBL-MIFIR-003","UK-MiFIR","UK SI 2017/701 Art.26(1) — Best Execution Reporting","Report on the quality of execution on a regular basis; take reasonable steps to obtain the best possible result for clients when executing orders","Market Integrity","FCA","3 Jan 2018","UK best execution reporting requirements broadly aligned with EU MiFID II but maintained through the UK Onshoring Regulations; divergence risk as EU continues to amend rules post-Brexit","Covered","CTL-CAP-001 (linked)","Best execution policy documentation; RTS 27 (execution venue) and RTS 28 (annual best execution) reports where applicable","SMF16",""],
["OBL-MIFIR-004","UK-MiFIR; UK MAR","UK MAR Art.16 — Suspicious Transaction and Order Reporting (STOR)","Report to the FCA any transaction or order which there are reasonable grounds to suspect involves or might involve market abuse; submit STOR as soon as reasonably practicable","Market Integrity","FCA","3 Jan 2018","UK STOR obligation aligned with EU MAR but operationalised through FCA GABRIEL portal; post-Brexit UK MAR enforcement is by FCA independently of ESMA","Covered","CTL-CAP-003","STOR submission log with FCA acknowledgement; surveillance alert log; market abuse investigation records","SMF16",""],
["OBL-MIFIR-005","UK-MiFIR; FCA SYSC","SYSC 10.1.3R / UK-MiFIR — Front Running and Conflicts of Interest Prevention","Establish effective arrangements to prevent market abuse including front-running; ensure Chinese walls are maintained between advisory and trading functions","Market Integrity","FCA","3 Jan 2018","UK conflicts of interest and Chinese wall requirements maintained under UK-MiFIR and SYSC; no material post-Brexit divergence at this date","Covered","CTL-CAP-003 (linked)","Conflicts of interest policy; Chinese wall procedures; surveillance alert log for insider trading and front-running scenarios","SMF16",""],
["OBL-EMIR-001","UK EMIR (SI 2013/504 as retained and amended); EMIR REFIT (effective April 2024 UK)","UK EMIR Art.9 (REFIT) — Trade Reporting Obligation","Report details of all OTC and ETD derivatives contracts to a UK Trade Repository; report must include counterparty information, trade details and lifecycle events in ISO 20022 format (approximately 203 fields as at REFIT implementation); report no later than T+1","Market Integrity","FCA / BoE","April 2024 (REFIT implementation in UK)","UK EMIR REFIT implementation April 2024 differs from EU EMIR REFIT implementation April 2024 in certain field specifications and CCP equivalence determinations. Firms operating in both jurisdictions maintain separate reporting stacks.","Covered","CTL-CAP-002","DTCC DerivServ UK submission log; field mapping validation log; reconciliation sign-off with break analysis","SMF16","UK EMIR REFIT diverged from EU EMIR REFIT in implementation details — parallel stacks required for EU-operating firms"],
["OBL-EMIR-002","UK EMIR","UK EMIR Art.11 — Risk Mitigation for Non-Cleared OTC Derivatives","Apply risk mitigation techniques to all non-cleared OTC derivative contracts including: timely confirmation; portfolio reconciliation; dispute resolution; variation margin exchange; initial margin exchange where applicable","Market Integrity","FCA","August 2012 (ongoing amendments)","UK EMIR risk mitigation requirements maintained under retained EU law with some UK-specific regulatory guidance; broadly aligned with EU requirements but supervised by FCA independently","Covered","CTL-CAP-004","MarkitWIRE/DTCC confirmation log; reconciliation breaks report; margin call and response log","SMF16",""],
["OBL-EMIR-003","UK EMIR","UK EMIR Art.4 — Clearing Obligation","Clear all OTC derivative contracts subject to the clearing obligation through a UK-authorised CCP (e.g. LCH, ICE Clear Europe); maintain appropriate accounts at CCP","Market Integrity","FCA / BoE","August 2012","UK clearing obligation maintained under retained EU law; FCA and BoE jointly supervise UK CCPs; CCP equivalence determinations are UK-specific post-Brexit","Covered","CTL-CAP-002 (linked)","Clearing account agreement with UK-authorised CCP; clearing threshold monitoring; cleared derivatives register","SMF16","UK CCP equivalence determinations are UK-specific and can diverge from EU equivalence decisions"],
["OBL-EMIR-004","UK EMIR; FSMA 2023","UK EMIR Art.26 (REFIT) — Valuation and Collateral Reporting","Report daily mark-to-market or mark-to-model valuations and collateral posted for all OTC derivative contracts to a UK Trade Repository","Market Integrity","FCA","April 2024 (REFIT)","UK EMIR REFIT introduced significant changes to valuation reporting fields; ISO 20022 standard for collateral reporting is new as of April 2024 in UK","Covered","CTL-CAP-002","Daily valuation and collateral report submission log; DTCC DerivServ UK acknowledgement","SMF16","REFIT April 2024 introduced material new obligations — firms still in remediation of REFIT field compliance"],
["OBL-PSR-001","PSR PS23/3 — APP Fraud Reimbursement","PSR PS23/3 (effective 7 October 2024) — Mandatory Reimbursement Obligation","Sending and receiving payment service providers must reimburse victims of authorised push payment fraud up to the reimbursement limit (£85,000 as at Q1 2026); 50/50 liability split between sending PSP and receiving PSP; reimbursement within 5 business days of claim","Conduct","PSR","7 Oct 2024","No direct US equivalent. US Regulation E covers unauthorised electronic fund transfers but there is no equivalent mandatory reimbursement regime for authorised push payment fraud.","Covered","CTL-PAY-001","APP fraud reimbursement register; reimbursement decision records; PSP-to-PSP liability split correspondence; PSR reporting data submissions","SMF22","No direct US equivalent — UK-specific mandatory reimbursement regime effective October 2024"],
["OBL-PSR-002","PSR PS23/3","PSR PS23/3 — Consumer Standard of Caution and Gross Negligence Exception","Firms may refuse reimbursement where the consumer failed to meet the consumer standard of caution, including providing false information; gross negligence must be evidenced, not assumed; vulnerable customer status is an absolute bar to applying the gross negligence exception","Conduct","PSR","7 Oct 2024","No direct US equivalent standard for assessing consumer caution in APP fraud reimbursement decisions — UK standard requires documented assessment of vulnerability and caution before declining reimbursement","Covered","CTL-PAY-001","Consumer standard of caution assessment records; vulnerability screening confirmation; decline decision rationale documentation","SMF22",""],
["OBL-PSR-003","PSRs 2017 Reg 100 / FCA SCA-RTS","PSRs 2017 Reg 100; FCA SCA-RTS — Strong Customer Authentication","Apply strong customer authentication for all in-scope electronic payment transactions requiring authentication at customer initiation; SCA must use at least two of: knowledge, possession or inherence factors","Conduct","FCA","14 Sep 2019","UK SCA-RTS implementation broadly aligned with EU PSD2 SCA requirements but maintained under UK-specific regulations post-Brexit; UK FCA has UK-specific exemption guidance","Covered","CTL-PAY-003","SCA authentication log; exemption application log with category and risk score; monthly SCA compliance report","SMF22",""],
["OBL-PSR-004","PSRs 2017; CoP Scheme Rules","PSRs 2017 / PSR Direction PSD2/1 — Confirmation of Payee","In-scope payment service providers must participate in the Confirmation of Payee service and respond to CoP requests; must present CoP result to payment initiators and record override decisions","Conduct","PSR","31 Mar 2024 (extended scope)","No direct US equivalent for a universal national name-matching service for electronic payments","Covered","CTL-PAY-001","CoP API call log with result and payment reference; override audit log; daily CoP mismatch rate report","SMF22","No direct US equivalent — UK-specific PSR-mandated infrastructure"],
["OBL-RFB-001","FSMA 2000 Part 9B; Ring-Fencing (Prohibited Activities) Order 2014","FSMA 2000 s.142A et seq — Ring-Fencing Structural Requirement","Banks whose core deposits exceed the prescribed threshold (£35 billion following Edinburgh Reforms 2022) must establish a Ring-Fenced Body (RFB) that is operationally separate from the Non-Ring-Fenced Body (NRFB); separate board; separate governance; separate capital","Prudential","PRA","1 Jan 2019","No direct US equivalent. Volcker Rule restricts certain proprietary trading but does not require structural separation of deposit-taking from investment banking activities through separate legal entities.","Covered","CTL-OPR-005","RFB board composition and governance documentation; capital adequacy evidence for RFB separately; operational separation evidence","SMF2","No direct US equivalent — UK structural reform unique to UK banking; £35bn threshold following Edinburgh Reforms 2022 (previously £25bn)"],
["OBL-RFB-002","FSMA 2000 Part 9B; Ring-Fencing (Prohibited Activities) Order 2014","Ring-Fencing (Prohibited Activities) Order 2014 — Prohibited Activities","The RFB must not carry out prohibited activities including: dealing in investments as principal (other than permitted ancillary purposes); dealing in commodities; certain securitisation activities; certain derivative transactions (other than qualifying hedging)","Prudential","PRA","1 Jan 2019","No direct US equivalent for a statutory prohibited activities list applying to a separately constituted ring-fenced body","Covered","CTL-OPR-005","Monthly prohibited activity boundary review report; product registry showing RFB/NRFB designation for each product; 0 prohibited activity incidents in breach register","SMF2","No direct US equivalent — ring-fencing prohibited activities are UK banking law specific"],
["OBL-RFB-003","FSMA 2000 Part 9B; Ring-Fencing Monitor Rules","FSMA 2000 s.142K — Ring-Fencing Monitor Annual Report","The Ring-Fenced Body must appoint a Ring-Fencing Monitor to review and report annually on whether the firm is complying with ring-fencing requirements; the monitor's report must be submitted to the PRA","Prudential","PRA","1 Jan 2019","No direct US equivalent for a mandatory independent monitor of structural separation","Covered","CTL-OPR-005","Ring-Fencing Monitor appointment documentation; annual Ring-Fencing Monitor report; PRA submission confirmation","SMF2","No direct US equivalent — UK-specific governance requirement"],
["OBL-RFB-004","FSMA 2000 Part 9B; CRR (as retained)","FSMA 2000 Part 9B / PRA Rulebook — Intra-Group Exposure Limits for RFB","Transactions between the RFB and the NRFB (and other non-ring-fenced group entities) must be priced at arm's length and must not exceed the large exposures limit in aggregate; specific reporting requirements apply to intra-group transactions","Prudential","PRA","1 Jan 2019","No direct US equivalent for arm's length pricing requirements on intra-group transactions as between structurally separate deposit-taking and investment banking entities","Covered","CTL-OPR-005 (linked)","Intra-group transaction pricing documentation; arm's length evidence (transfer pricing methodology); intra-group exposure reports to PRA","SMF2",""],
["OBL-RFB-005","FSMA 2000 Part 9B","FSMA 2000 s.142L — RFB Separate Recovery and Resolution Planning","The Ring-Fenced Body must maintain a separate recovery plan and contribute to the group resolution strategy; the recovery plan must reflect the RFB's structural separation and its distinct capital and operational position","Prudential","PRA","1 Jan 2019","While US banks must maintain recovery plans, the UK requirement for structurally separate RFB recovery planning with distinct IBS, capital and operational scope has no direct US equivalent","Covered","CTL-OPR-002 (linked)","RFB recovery plan document; board approval record; PRA submission confirmation; annual review evidence","SMF2",""],
["OBL-GDPR-001","UK GDPR (retained EU law); DPA 2018","UK GDPR Art.6 — Lawful Basis for Processing","Process personal data only where one of the lawful bases applies (consent, contract, legal obligation, vital interests, public task, legitimate interests); document lawful basis for each processing activity; personal data may not be processed without a lawful basis","Data","ICO","25 May 2018","UK GDPR is retained EU law amended by the Data Protection, Privacy and Electronic Communications (Amendments etc.) (EU Exit) Regulations 2019; broadly aligned with EU GDPR but UK ICO operates independently of EDPB","Covered","CTL-ONB-003 (data retention linked)","Record of Processing Activities (ROPA) documenting lawful basis for each banking processing activity; DPIA records where required","SMF16","UK GDPR diverges from EU GDPR in some post-Brexit amendments but core obligations broadly aligned"],
["OBL-GDPR-002","UK GDPR; DPA 2018","UK GDPR Art.33 — 72-Hour Breach Notification to ICO","In the event of a personal data breach likely to result in a risk to the rights and freedoms of natural persons, notify the ICO without undue delay and where feasible within 72 hours of becoming aware; include prescribed information in the notification","Data","ICO","25 May 2018","UK 72-hour notification deadline aligned with EU GDPR but administered by UK ICO independently; UK ICO has UK-specific enforcement guidance","Covered","CTL-OPR-004","Breach notification record with timeline; ICO notification reference and confirmation; assessment records for below-threshold breaches","SMF16",""],
["OBL-GDPR-003","UK GDPR; DPA 2018","UK GDPR Art.17 — Right to Erasure; DPA 2018 Schedule 2 — Crime Prevention Exemption","Erase personal data when a valid erasure request is received and no overriding legal obligation or exemption applies; DPA 2018 Schedule 2 para 2 permits withholding personal data where compliance would prejudice prevention or detection of crime or prosecution of offenders","Data","ICO","25 May 2018","UK DPA 2018 Schedule 2 financial crime prevention exemption is a UK-specific framing of the GDPR public interest restriction; used extensively in AML/sanctions contexts to override data subject rights requests","Covered","CTL-ONB-003 (linked)","Erasure request handling records with exemption application documentation; financial crime exemption log; legal review records for complex cases","SMF16","DPA 2018 Schedule 2 financial crime exemption is UK-specific — allows banks to refuse erasure requests where AML retention obligations apply"],
["OBL-GDPR-004","UK GDPR; DPA 2018","UK GDPR Art.15 — Data Subject Access Requests (DSAR)","Respond to data subject access requests within one calendar month of receipt (extendable to three months for complex requests); provide a copy of all personal data processed about the data subject","Data","ICO","25 May 2018","UK DSAR response timeline of one month (extendable to three) mirrors EU GDPR but DPA 2018 complex case extensions and financial crime exemptions create UK-specific operational requirements","Covered","CTL-ONB-003 (linked)","DSAR handling records with receipt date, response date and any extension notification; financial crime exemption application log for banking DSARs","SMF16",""],
["OBL-GDPR-005","DPA 2018","DPA 2018 Schedule 2 — Financial Crime Exemptions","Apply exemptions where compliance with UK GDPR individual rights (access, erasure, restriction) would be likely to prejudice the prevention or detection of crime or the prosecution of offenders — document and justify each application of the exemption","Data","ICO","25 May 2018","Banking-specific exemption frequently invoked in AML/financial crime investigations; must be documented on a case-by-case basis; UK-specific Schedule 2 framing with no direct EU equivalent carve-out","Covered","CTL-ONB-003 (linked)","Exemption logging records; financial crime override documentation; DPIA carve-out documentation","SMF16","UK-specific Schedule 2 exemption — must be documented per case, not applied systematically"],
